In OpenROAD, you can use end-of-line comments to comment out single lines or the ends of partial lines. To create an end-of-line comment, simply precede the comment with "//". For example:
```
// This is a single-line comment
insert into employees(salary, age)
values(:salfield, :agefield); //This is a comment
commit work;
```
In this example, the second line contains an end-of-line comment that explains what the comment on the preceding line does. You can also use "//" to comment out lines of code by placing it at the beginning of a line:
```
//insert into employees(salary, age)
//values(:salfield, :agefield);
//commit work;
```
In this case, the first two lines are commented out and will not be executed.

In OpenROAD, you can use block comments for single-line or multi-line comments. A block comment begins with "/*" on the left and ends with "*/". For example:
```
/* This is a single-line block comment */
```
Here's an example of a multi-line block comment that explains how to perform a specific task in your 4GL script:
```
/*
** This is a multi-line block
** comment. It explains the steps to calculate the total salary for each employee.
*/
set v_total to 0;
loop through employees;
    set v_total equal (v_total + :salary);
end loop;
display "Total Salary: " + string(v_total);
```
In this example, the block comment explains the steps to calculate the total salary for each employee and includes code snippets that demonstrate how to perform these steps. Block comments are useful when you need to provide longer explanations or comment out larger blocks of code.

Here's an example of a commented-out line using block comments in OpenROAD:
```
insert into employees(salary, age)
/* This is a line of code that is being temporarily disabled. It will not be executed until the comment is removed */
values(:salfield, :agefield);
commit work;
```
In this example, the commented-out line `values(:salfield, :agefield);` is temporarily disabled and will not be executed until the surrounding block comments are removed. This can be useful when you want to test different parts of your code or disable specific sections for debugging purposes without having to remove them completely from your script.

Here is an example of a commented-out multi-line code block in OpenROAD:

```
